&gt;snip&lt;
&gt;the lemurs internal state 
&gt;does not go through a series of defined stages each corresponding to
one 
&gt;decision. Instead it just acts in a certain way when exposed to certain
&gt;stimuli. 
&gt;snip&gt; 

Acting in a certain way seems like a suitable description for a
&#39;decision.&#39;
One any given input, or sequence of inputs, some particular behavior 
will result. That could be anything. But it is always one behaviour. The
selection of a single behavior (because simultaneous behavior is
impossible) 
seems to constitute a decision. 
I think it is very necessary that the definition of a decision be so
vague. A 
similar description for memory could be: Memory is the effect of history
on a decision. 
This seems to me to be different than the electronic idea of memory,
where 
data is stored for retrieval. Like you said, Ion, memory is not the part
of a 
system that remember. It&#39;s a system that can remember. In a computer, 
the idea of a part of the system that can remember means we have RAM, 
Hard drives, video buffers, and CPU cache. Maybe I&#39;m stretching the idea
a bit, but the &#39;part of the system that remembers&#39; has been distributed
a 
lot over time. Just an interesting side thought... 

&gt; snip &lt;
&gt; Hmm, I think you may be a little off track here. The lemur almost 
&gt; certainly did not make the decision to select the pictures. I&#39;d
imagine 
&gt; that the scientist trained it to do so, in return for a reward,
probably 
&gt; food. The lemur did not do something as interesting as: &quot;Here are 
&gt; pictures. They are the same pictures as the other pictures. The order
is 
&gt; different. I wonder what happens if I...&quot; 
&gt; snip &lt;

In a very literal sense your saying that the lemur didn&#39;t speak english.
Distinct decisions can certainly be made without translating them into 
english. When your typing an e-mail, I don&#39;t think explicitly to myself 
&quot;Hmm, the keys are arranged in a similar order. I will find the key &#39;f&#39;
and 
push that key. then I will find the &#39;i&#39; key, and I will push that.&quot; 
Clearly ridiculous. Most behavior does not require high level thought. 
In addition, most (if not all) behavior is hierarchical, meaning that
you go 
to the fridge because you are hungry, and you remember there is food 
in the fridge. (going to the fridge is a decision) you use your arm and 
hand to open the fridge door because you are going to the fridge. You 
use your other arm and hand to grab the food. You remember to close 
the door, because you always close the door when your done with the 
fridge. We can define the crap out of all the steps we don&#39;t really
think 
about, but like you said, it would be really hard to describe the
&#39;smallest&#39; 
step because at some point they are nerve signals for muscle
contractions. 

I think decisions are a relatively continuous process, and I think
memory 
is an equally continuous process. I think an ANN who&#39;s neural functions 
depend on history could be more intelligent that a network of the same 
size that does not use history. With computers we can cheat, and
actually 
store data into buffers, and apply any transfer function with this data
buffer,
when biological systems must use material/chemical memory who&#39;s 
parameters cannot be played with. 

I don&#39;t think this idea will produce a long term memory, but I think a
powerful
short term memory can be developed this way. 

Chad 

